{"key":"processedPost-11725231","value":{"id":11725231,"first":11723689,"last":11819557,"when":1261932365,"utime":"12/27/09 06:46 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br /><strong>RedDevil420 said:</strong><br />Nah, if you mist up into the air, a nice light mist sprinkles on the mushrooms and adds a humididy cloud.&nbsp; The idea is that you want the caps to return to being slightly dry after you fan them because if it is really soaked it can contam easier.&nbsp; Also, I've had defects with overwatering directly.&nbsp; Soaking them is not good.<br />You should have enough water in the casing and substrate for the flush, else dunk it.&nbsp; Misting is just to add a bit of humidity to the surface.&nbsp; You shouldnt need to soak it.</blockquote><br />This is absolutely incorrect, and based on ten year old advice that for some reason keeps getting repeated, fucking up people's projects.<br />Misting is NOT to provide humidity.&nbsp; That is the job of the perlite.&nbsp; Misting is to replace the moisture that evaporates from the substrate due to giving proper fresh air exchange.&nbsp; Even at 99% humidity, your cakes will dry out if they're getting the proper fresh air.&nbsp; In addition, as fruits form, they draw lots of water from the substrate, and will totally dry out a small cake before the flush is finished if you don't replace that water by misting.<br />RR"}}